SAPOVIRUS - NEW ZEALAND: (GISBORNE) HOSPITAL OUTBREAK
*****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 2 Dec 2013
Source: The Gisborne Herald [edited]
http://www.gisborneherald.co.nz/article/?id=35098


One positive result for sapovirus infection has been confirmed at Gisborne Hospital. Tairawhiti District Health Medical Officer of Health Dr Geoffrey Cramp said further results were needed but at this stage the result indicated [a] sapovirus was the cause of the gastroenteritis outbreak at this hospital last week [week of 25 Nov 2013]. Sapovirus [infection] is a diarrhoeal gastroenteritis similar to norovirus [infection], but milder. All results so far were negative for norovirus, he said. There have been only 2 new cases -- both staff members -- at the weekend [30 Nov-1 Dec 2013] and 5 patients were in isolation as of this morning [2 Dec 2013].

Over the weekend, hospital staff worked to isolate cases and to use personal protection when entering their rooms. It looked like the precautionary measures taken had helped to bring the outbreak under control, said Dr Cramp. The public are still advised to limit visits to the hospital unless it is "absolutely essential" and to avoid bringing young children or people with low immunity to the hospital.

Staff who were affected by the virus should not return to work until 48 hours after being clear of symptoms, he said. Hand washing was imperative. He said prospective visitors should make use of the hand sanitiser dispensers available at key entry points to the hospital.

[Byline: Marino Harker-Smith]

