[The highly contagious noroviruses are responsible for most gastroenteritis outbreaks in institutional settings, on cruise ships, and in schools. However, a subset of viral gastroenteritis outbreaks in which norovirus is not detected may be due to viruses such as astroviruses, adenoviruses, or rotavirus. Sapovirus, a pathogen discovered in 1977 from the same family as norovirus (_Caliciviridae_), is an underappreciated but important cause of norovirus-negative outbreaks.

The family _Caliciviridae_ contains 5 genera _Sapovirus_, _Nebovirus_, _Norovirus_, _Lagovirus_, and _Vesivirus_, which include Sapovirus (SaV), Newbury-1 virus, Norwalk virus (NoV), Rabbit hemorrhagic disease virus (RHDV), and Feline calicivirus (FCV), respectively. SaV is a causative agent of (usually) mild gastroenteritis in children and adults. SaV can be divided into 5 genogroups (GI-GV), among which GI, GII, GIV, and GV are known to infect humans, whereas SaV GIII infects only porcine species.

Sapovirus was first detected in 1977 as the cause of a gastroenteritis outbreak in a home for infants in Sapporo, Japan, and was thereafter reported primarily among young children with acute gastroenteritis. After sapovirus diagnostic RT-PCR was developed, sapovirus outbreaks were discovered in long-term care facilities for the elderly.

Gisborne is a city in northeastern New Zealand and the largest settlement in the Gisborne Region. It has a population of around 34 800, and is named after an early Colonial Secretary William Gisborne. An interactive map of the Gisborne Region can be accessed at http://map.bluecastle.co.nz/Gisborne-map.htm. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/9nYb.]
